    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2135127">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2135127">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2135127)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2135127">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1413753796 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Oct 2014 21:23</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2135127">
									

<p>Little moments of characterization. I'm going to upvote this one as a matter of support for this sort of thing in extended tale arcs. The key to making a successful piece of short fiction independent of the format is to give the reader a reason to care about the characters, and to invest themselves in the outcome of the events of the story. This helps that along and sets things up for the next installments. For the most part, these are feeling more and more like real people.</p>
<p>I also enjoy the perspective of this series. I think I've mentioned this previously, but I like the setting of the story in Japan, as a global organization of any sort is going to want a significant presence in East Asia. More than that, though, I like the weaving of different elements of Japanese culture into how the characters perceive events and how they act. It gives it a nice Eastern flavor, and that's fairly unique on the wiki.</p>
<p>I do wish the interaction between the Foundation agents was a <em>little</em> less directly related. The old veteran/nervous rookie dynamic is okay, but I think Yuudai's dialogue could have been a little more deftly handled. It sounded like a pastiche of cop dramas that I've seen a thousand times before, and that may have been the intent, but compared with everyone else, he was a little off.</p>
<p>Still, solid work.</p>

							</div>

								
					
